High Priority:

Data Sufficiency & Label MaturitySevere data downsizing: Discarding 18 months of data for a 2-week window severely limits the model's ability to learn rare fraud patterns.
Label maturity lag: Fraud chargebacks typically take 30 to 90 days to surface. The past 2 weeks of data will contain incomplete fraud labels, training the model on false negatives.
No behavioral history: A 2-week window makes it impossible to build long-term user baseline profiles or calculate historical spending habits.
Missing seasonality: The model will fail to capture cyclic fraud trends, holiday shopping spikes, or monthly patterns.

Medium Priority: Feature Scarcity & Cardinality
Extremely sparse categories: Matching 223 payment processors and 47 countries against only 2 weeks of data results in severe data sparsity.
No velocity features: The dataset lacks vital fraud signals like transaction frequency within the last 1, 10, or 60 minutes.
No network or location signals: Important fraud indicators like IP address, proxy usage, and email age are missing.

Low Priority:
Data ConsistencyCurrency conversion ambiguity: The feature listed is amount_usd, but the data contains 8 currencies. It is unclear if conversions use historical or real-time rates.

